[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, as I have famously said on the channel many times, there is no right or wrong way to prompt. And that continues to be true, but there are certainly some practices that will work better than others. And lately, I have seen a bit of a trend, particularly with C-Dance 2.0,'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that leans into what might be considered over-prompting. Although, some of these results are going to surprise you. So, today we\'re going to crank the volume knob on our references and prompts to see exactly where that sweet spot is.'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Turn it up to 11. If it doesn\'t go to 11, then just turn it to 10, cuz that\'s kind of 11 as well, right? Kicking off. Lately, and particularly since the release of GPT Image 2, I\'ve seen a lot of experimental omni'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference one-sheet techniques that, well, I mean, they can look really great. But also, I\'ve seen a number of them that might be asking too much of the model in like one go. Now, I do have to say C-Dance 2.0 is a very good model.'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, even when you\'re giving it context overload like this, I mean, it\'s still going to end up pulling something pretty remarkable off. But, and as I think we\'re going to see here today, because C-Dance is capable of taking up to nine'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different references in the omni mode, um by sort of splitting them up and stacking them, well, that\'s where you get the really insane results. Kind of. Sometimes. Now, a quick note on today\'s experiment. Uh we\'re going to be working'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'over on polo.ai. Uh I will say that all of the ideas here are global, but you know, obviously, at some point we\'re going to take a quick tour of everything that polo.ai has to offer. Look, they were kind enough to'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sponsor today\'s video. Let\'s pay them some due. And also, I mean, they\'re it\'s a good platform. We\'ll chat more about that later. Anyhow, back to the experiment. So, starting off by creating a character sheet of flamethrower girl in her jungle adventure outfit. So,'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'utilizing our base nano banana image model for flamethrower girl\'s jungle outfit, uh and then upgrading that via Image 2, uh the prompt is there if you want to like screenshot that and use'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that as a template. Um we ended up with this as a result, which uh it looks pretty good. I will say that image two tends to have a slightly painterly look to its skin textures at least um when you\'re doing model sheets like this.'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Although, you know, by the time you bring this into C Dance, that kind of auto-corrects itself. So, kicking off using our character reference sheet with a reference to video, once again C Dance 2.0, uh we\'re going to do this in 21:9'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and at 15 seconds. The prompt is very like human-written, not LLM-driven, of a cinematic jungle adventure with the character removing a ancient artifact from a jungle pyramid. Uh yeah, very, you know, uh Tomb Raider Lara Croft'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coded prompt there. I mean, overall, I got to say not too'

[02:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bad. I really like that opening establishing shot. Uh our girl obviously remains uh very consistent throughout all of this. Uh action is pretty good, although there are some issues like where did the idol go there? And then when she comes outside, obviously who\'s'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'firing those arrows at her? Interestingly, I accidentally ran her character sheet as image to video, and actually it ended up kind of proving a pet theory of mine. Uh check this out. I mean, overall, a pretty great output'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'again. We There is a weird issue here with like a ghost version of her in the background, but I really do like all of like the emoting and acting and action and camera movement in this output as well. And this is again, this is image to video, which again I The pet theory'

[03:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of mine is that uh you know, the OmniRef model and the uh image to video model, it\'s the same model. Now, as we begin turning up the volume and adding in more reference and context, I do want to note that, uh, the way that I\'m approaching'

[03:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
