[16:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mean, but for the most part, it, you know, C Dance managed to to kind of get through it all minus the fact that it is an alternate ending in which Jungle Girl does not escape. But, I think the important thing to note is that as we\'ve seen going much tighter with prompts and'

[16:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of being a little more loose with prompts is that not not any one of them was perfect. And that\'s kind of the sneaky thing that I wanted to point out by showcasing all of these as one shots is that, you know, they\'re they\'ve all'

[17:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'got really great stuff in them, but not any one of them is completely perfect. So, you know, your best bet, again, as always is to roll like two or three of them, maybe, and then you know, head into your editor and chop up the best'

[17:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parts. As I said at the beginning of 2026, the biggest skill that you can level up on with AI filmmaking is of course editing. And you know, what I did not see at that time was our push into agentic filmmaking. Polo obviously has'

[17:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'their agent on board as well. I\'m not still not completely sold on them in terms of outputting like whole hog. I think that they can be very useful for generating and brainstorming up shots, but ultimately at the end of'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the day, you know, if you want a polished piece, you\'re going to need to roll up your sleeves and get into that non-linear editor. So, that\'s it for today. I do hope you found this pretty interesting. I found it pretty interesting. We should probably go check in on flame thrower'

